      <h2>What About Horsepower and Tank Size?</h2>
      <p>There's a common misconception that larger HP numbers require larger tanks. That's not really how it works. A 6-gallon vac can have a 5 HP motor (like the STEALTHSONIC), and a 16-gallon vac might have a 4 HP motor. The motor and tank are independent specs.</p>
      <p>However, in practice, larger tanks usually come with higher-HP motors because you need more suction to fill the larger volume efficiently. Here's the typical pairing:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>4 HP:</strong> Usually found on 6-gallon compact vacs</li>
        <li><strong>5 HP:</strong> Common on 6–10 gallon mid-range models</li>
        <li><strong>6–6.5 HP:</strong> Standard on 10–16 gallon large-capacity vacs</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The exception is DEWALT's STEALTHSONIC line, where noise-reduction engineering sometimes trades peak HP for quieter operation without sacrificing real-world suction.</p>

      <h2>Can You Have Too Much Capacity?</h2>
      <p>Surprisingly, yes. Here are the downsides of oversizing:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Weight.</strong> A 16-gallon tank made of poly can weigh 20+ pounds empty. Add debris and you're pushing 60+ pounds. If you regularly need to move it between floors, that gets old fast.</li>
        <li><strong>Storage.</strong> A 16-gallon shop vac dominates truck bed or van space. If you carry multiple tools, a 6 or 9-gallon unit is much easier to fit around.</li>
        <li><strong>Cleaning.</strong> Bigger tanks take longer to clean and dry after wet pickup. A 6-gallon tank you can rinse and flip dry in 2 minutes; a 16-gallon takes 10+ minutes.</li>
        <li><strong>Cost.</strong> Larger models cost more upfront and replacement filters are typically more expensive for larger-diameter tanks.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The key is to match the tank size to your actual debris volume, not your perception of "more is better." If you empty a 6-gallon tank 3 times per job and each job takes 4 hours, that's fine — only 3 interruptions. But if you're emptying it 10+ times per day, you need to size up.</p>

      <h2>Final Recommendation</h2>
      <p>For most individual contractors, a <strong>6 or 9-gallon shop vac</strong> is the right choice — portable enough to carry, capable enough for daily use. The <strong>DEWALT DXV06P 6 Gallon</strong> (4.7★) is our top pick for this category.</p>
      <p>For general contractors and remodelers who work on medium to large projects, a <strong>10-gallon vac</strong> like the <strong>STANLEY 10 Gallon</strong> (4.5★) or <strong>DEWALT DXV09PZ 9 Gallon</strong> (4.6★) offers the best balance.</p>
      <p>And for large crews and heavy construction, the <strong>DEWALT DXV16PA 16 Gallon</strong> (4.7★) is unmatched for uninterrupted cleanup power.</p>
      <p>Whichever size you choose, a quality shop vac will pay for itself in saved time and cleaner job sites within the first few months.</p>

